{"id":"0812.3279","submitter":"Houri Ziaeepour","authors":"Houri Ziaeepour","title":"Gamma Ray Bursts Cook Book II: Simulation","comments":"24 pages, 16 figure(MNRAS LaTex); v2: Simulations and plots modified.\n  No modification in conclusions, submitted version","journal-ref":"Mon.Not.R.Astron.Soc., 397 (2009) 386","doi":"10.1111/j.1365-2966.2009.14928.x","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In Paper I we presented a detailed formulation of the relativistic shocks and\nsynchrotron emission in the context of Gamma-Ray Burst (GRB) physics. To see\nhow well this model reproduces the observed characteristics of the GRBs and\ntheir afterglows, here we present the results of some simulations based on this\nmodel. They are meant to reproduce the prompt and afterglow emission in some\nintervals of time during a burst. We show that this goal is achieved for both\nshort and long GRBs and their afterglows, at least for part of the parameter\nspace. Moreover, these results are the evidence of the physical relevance of\nthe two phenomenological models we have suggested in Paper I for the evolution\nof the {\\it active region}, the synchrotron emitting region in a shock. The\ndynamical active region model seems to reproduce the observed characteristics\nof prompt emissions and late afterglow better than the quasi-steady model which\nis more suitable for the onset of afterglows. Therefore these simulations\nconfirm the arguments presented in Paper I about the behaviour of these models\nbased on their physical properties.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 17 Dec 2008 12:48:56 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 18 Mar 2009 18:55:23 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-05-13"}
